      <div class="paragraph">
        Again, we are all stubborn about our preferences. You might disagree with me and say that your preferences are definitive. Your disagreement is the reason why I am writing this blog. I want to create an alternate way of thinking about our preferences, with the hope that I can help people explore options that can potentially turn out to be better than their current preferences.
      </div>
      <h1>Opening your mind</h1>
      <div class="paragraph">
        To become mindful, recognizing your confirmation bias is the first step. First, think about your favourite course. Why do you like it? Is it because it is easy and you love the satisfaction of success? If it is, I would recommend exploring more options. There are likely other things with better reasons for you to enjoy. Think you already tried other options? Then what made you dislike them? Was it because they didn't make sense or felt useless? If that is the reason, I would encourage you to try them again, with optimism.
      </div>
      <div class="paragraph">
        We are always unconsciously making comparisons between our preferences. When we believe we have a preference, we eliminate our possibility of continuing to look for something else. For example, students always say “I'm more of a math person, I can't do art!”. When this happens, we become ignorant to the preferential features of other options. Over time, this inconspicuous feedback loop induces confirmation bias that makes us dislike those options.
      </div>
      <div class="paragraph">
        Unlike the loop between other human beings, discussed in the beginning of the blog, we don't escape this loop as we mature. The only way to get away from it is to start all over with optimism. Only look at the favourable traits in things. The other traits won't matter because our ambition and determination will incentivize us to chase our goals regardless of the costs. When doing this, also pay careful attention to the satisfaction of fulfillment. You might intuitively like a subject from the initial fulfillment. However, this satisfaction can occur on every subject, and conversely, can fade away from the subject you like as it gets harder.
      </div>
