      <h1>My story</h1>
      <div class="paragraph">
        In grade 11, I loved chemistry for the satisfaction of seeing my drudgery paying off in my grades. I disliked history since it was challenging for me to memorize the events and dates. I never even considered taking arts because not only did it not make sense to me, I also didn't see any pragmatic applications of it. Not to mention people were always talking about the difficulty of getting a job with an art degree. One day, my social teacher did his usual enlightenment to the class:
      </div>
      <div class="quote last">
        Sometimes, people tell me that they are more of a science person, and are not a social type of person. To them, I say: “Why not be both?”. You guys are still young. It is never too late to learn something. I didn't know how to say “Hello” in spanish until 23, and I am now a fluent spanish teacher.
      </div>
      <div class="paragraph">
        His message awoke me. Indeed, we are the only people limiting ourselves. Everyone around us is empathetic of our preferences. The only factors stopping us from trying is our stubbornness, fear of change, and confirmation bias. Although history is still not my favourite subject, I now see the benefits of taking it, and certainly don't dislike it anymore. This paradigm shift in perspective makes me more engaged in history classes, which facilitates me in learning and memorizing concepts that I found difficult. For art, my change in perspective was even greater. I became an aspiring art student after recognizing the level of thoughtfulness in artists' minds, and understood that art is more than just what we see on the canvas. Art involves perspectives, communication, mindfulness, and much more other pragmatic skills. On the other hand, chemistry became harder, and without that feeling of accomplishment, I realized that chemistry is not as interesting to me as I thought it was.
      </div>
      <h1>Summary</h1>
      <div class="paragraph">
        Stubbornness, fear of change, and confirmation bias unconsciously hinder us from trying out subjects unfamiliar to us. However, we can and we should have multiple passions, instead of limiting ourselves to stick to just one. To mitigate this, be open to changes and new perspectives, and don't be afraid to try something you don't like. The time spent on learning a thing that you later find to be uninteresting is not a waste of time at all, it is a process of understanding yourself.
